,"Storage capacity of 150 mL","Stratified squamous epithelial lining"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe gallbladder wall has several distinct layers. The innermost layer (mucosa) is lined by \u003Cstrong\u003Esimple columnar epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E with microvilli that increase the surface area for absorption. The gallbladder has a much smaller \u003Cstrong\u003Estorage capacity\u003C/strong\u003E than suggested, typically 30-50 mL. The gallbladder does have a \u003Cstrong\u003Esubmucosa layer\u003C/strong\u003E which contains blood vessels, lymphatics and nerves. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elamina propria\u003C/strong\u003E consists of loose connective tissue, not dense irregular connective tissue. The mucosal lining is not \u003Cstrong\u003Estratified squamous epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E as this would not be suitable for the absorption and secretory functions of the gallbladder.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The gallbladder has a storage capacity of approximately 30-50 mL of bile","The gallbladder wall consists of mucosa, muscularis, and serosa layers","The gallbladder mucosa contains simple columnar epithelium with microvilli"],"references":["Behar, Jose. \u0022Physiology and pathophysiology of the biliary tract: the gallbladder and sphincter of Oddi\u2014a review.\u0022 International Scholarly Research Notices 2013.1 (2013): 837630.","Dave HD, Shumway KR, Al Obaidi NM. Physiology, Biliary. [Updated 2022 Dec 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537107/","Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45.","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenter